# fetch_isoforms_hs.py

> Fetch exon- and isoform-level annotations from Ensembl human genes (GRCh38) via the REST API.  
> Generates an **Exon-Resolved Protein Mapping Table (ERPM)**: a per-exon TSV with genomic coordinates, CDS offsets, nucleotide sequences, and derived protein sequences per exon.

## What this tool does

`bin/fetch_isoforms_hs.py` queries the [Ensembl REST API](https://rest.ensembl.org) and builds a flat, denormalized table where **each row is one exon instance in one transcript**. It calculates the reading frame at every splice junction and extracts the exact amino acid sub-sequence contributed by each exon, including the "junctional" C-terminal residue split across the intron boundary.

This is useful for:
- **Splice-aware variant interpretation** — map a genomic variant to its affected exon and protein residue
- **Exon-skipping analysis** — know the exact protein sequence lost when an exon is skipped
- **CRISPR guide design** — target exons with precise awareness of coding frame
- **Isoform comparison** — compare exon composition and protein output across transcripts of the same gene

## Quick Start

Requires Python 3.8+ and `requests`, `pandas`.

```bash
pip install requests pandas

# Single gene
python bin/fetch_isoforms_hs.py --genes ENSG00000141510 --output-dir out/

# Multiple genes
python bin/fetch_isoforms_hs.py --genes ENSG00000141510,ENSG00000139618 --output-dir out/

# Batch mode from file (one Ensembl gene ID per line)
python bin/fetch_isoforms_hs.py --input-file genes.txt --output-dir out/
```

## Output format: Exon-Resolved Protein Mapping Table (ERPM)

One TSV file is written per gene:

```
out/ENSG00000141510_exons.tsv
```

### Column definitions

| Column | Type | Description |
|--------|------|-------------|
| `gene_id` | string | Ensembl gene ID (e.g., `ENSG00000141510`) |
| `gene_name` | string | HGNC gene symbol (e.g., `TP53`) |
| `transcript_id` | string | Ensembl transcript ID (e.g., `ENST00000413465`) |
| `transcript_name` | string | Transcript display name |
| `transcript_biotype` | string | Ensembl biotype (e.g., `protein_coding`, `nonsense_mediated_decay`) |
| `translation_id` | string | Ensembl protein ID (e.g., `ENSP00000410739`) |
| `exon_id` | string | Ensembl exon ID |
| `exon_number` | integer | Rank of this exon within the transcript (1-based, 5' to 3' transcript order) |
| `total_exons` | integer | Total number of exons in this transcript |
| `chromosome` | string | Chromosome name |
| `genomic_start` | integer | 1-based genomic start coordinate (Ensembl convention) |
| `genomic_end` | integer | 1-based genomic end coordinate (inclusive) |
| `strand` | integer | `1` (forward) or `-1` (reverse) |
| `exon_length` | integer | Length in nucleotides (`genomic_end - genomic_start + 1`) |
| `is_coding` | boolean | Whether this exon overlaps the CDS |
| `cds_start_nt_0based` | integer / empty | Start position of this exon's coding portion within the **spliced CDS** (0-based, half-open); empty string for non-coding exons |
| `cds_end_nt_0based_exclusive` | integer / empty | End position within the spliced CDS (exclusive); empty string for non-coding exons |
| `cds_frame_offset_start` | integer | Reading frame offset at the exon 5' boundary (`0`, `1`, or `2`; `-1` for non-coding exons) |
| `cds_frame_offset_end` | integer | Reading frame offset at the exon 3' boundary (`0`, `1`, or `2`; `-1` for non-coding exons) |
| `protein_start_aa_1based` | integer / empty | First amino acid position contributed by this exon's fully-contained codons (1-based, inclusive); empty string for non-coding exons |
| `protein_end_aa_1based` | integer / empty | Last amino acid position contributed by this exon's fully-contained codons (1-based, inclusive); empty string for non-coding exons |
| `exon_sequence` | string | Nucleotide sequence of the exon in genomic orientation by default; reverse-complemented to 5'→3' transcript orientation when `--reverse-complement-negative-strand` is used |
| `exon_protein_sequence` | string | Amino acid sub-sequence encoded by the fully-contained codons within this exon (excludes the junctional split-codon residue) |
| `junctional_Cterm` | string | The C-terminal amino acid residue whose codon is split across the splice junction (2 nt from this exon, 1 nt from the next); empty if the exon ends on a complete codon boundary |

### Coordinate system notes
- **Genomic coordinates** (`genomic_start`, `genomic_end`) follow the **1-based, inclusive Ensembl convention**.
- **CDS coordinates** (`cds_start_nt_0based`, `cds_end_nt_0based_exclusive`) follow **0-based, half-open** logic relative to the spliced coding sequence (i.e., after intron removal).
- **Protein coordinates** (`protein_start_aa_1based`, `protein_end_aa_1based`) are **1-based, inclusive** and cover only the fully-contained codons within the exon. The `junctional_Cterm` residue sits immediately after `protein_end_aa_1based` and is shared with the next exon.

## Command-line options

| Flag | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `--genes` | Comma-separated Ensembl gene IDs (e.g., `ENSG00000141510,ENSG00000139618`) |
| `--input-file` | Text file with one Ensembl gene ID per line |
| `--output-dir` | **Required.** Directory for output TSV files |
| `--no-protein-validation` | Enable retrieval and validation of Ensembl protein sequences (by default, validation is skipped) |
| `--reverse-complement-negative-strand` | Return negative-strand exon sequences in 5'→3' transcript orientation (reverse-complemented) |
| `--overwrite` | Overwrite existing output files |
| `-v`, `--verbose` | Print preview of the output dataframe to stderr |

## FAQ

### How do I fetch exon sequences for multiple genes at once?
Use `--input-file` with a text file containing one `ENSG` ID per line. The script processes genes sequentially and writes one TSV per gene.

### Can I reverse-complement negative-strand exons?
Yes. By default, exon sequences are returned in genomic orientation (5'→3' on the forward strand). Use `--reverse-complement-negative-strand` to return negative-strand exons in 5'→3' transcript orientation.

### How does this tool handle reading frames across splice junctions?
The tool tracks the cumulative CDS length upstream of each exon to determine the frame offset at the exon start. It extracts only the fully-contained codons for `exon_protein_sequence`, and reports the split-codon residue separately in `junctional_Cterm`. This ensures no amino acid is double-counted between adjacent exons.

### What is the `junctional_Cterm` column?
It is the single amino acid residue encoded by a split codon at the 3' end of the exon (2 nt from this exon, 1 nt from the next). This is critical for splice-aware variant interpretation, where a variant near the splice donor may alter this residue. If the exon ends on a complete codon boundary, this field is empty.

### Which Ensembl release and genome build does this use?
The script queries the live Ensembl REST API (`https://rest.ensembl.org`), which serves the current **GRCh38** human assembly. The specific Ensembl release version is determined by the API endpoint at runtime.

### What do empty values mean for non-coding exons?
For non-coding exons (`is_coding = False`), the CDS coordinate columns (`cds_start_nt_0based`, `cds_end_nt_0based_exclusive`) and protein coordinate columns (`protein_start_aa_1based`, `protein_end_aa_1based`) are empty strings, while `cds_frame_offset_start` and `cds_frame_offset_end` are set to `-1`.

